revision.text:
'''Akdalaite''' is a very rare [[mineral]] found in [[Kazakhstan]] and has the formula 5[[aluminum|Al]]<sub>2</sub>[[oxygen|O]]<sub>3</sub>·[[hydrogen|H]]<sub>2</sub>O.<ref>A New Occurrence and New Data on Akdalaite, a Retrograde Mineral from UHP Whiteschist, Kokchetav Massif, Northern Kazakhstan, Shyh-Lung Hwang, Pouyan Shen, Hao-Tsu Chu, Tzen-Fu Yui, International Geology Review, 48, 8, 2006, 754-764, {{doi|10.2747/0020-6814.48.8.754}}</ref> It was formerly believed to be 4[[aluminum|Al]]<sub>2</sub>[[oxygen|O]]<sub>3</sub>·[[hydrogen|H]]<sub>2</sub>O. It is therefore the same as [[tohdite]] an artificially produced phase. Studies on the crystal structure and spectra indicate that this is an aluminium oxide hydroxide.<ref>Ab-initio quantum mechanical study of akdalaite (5Al2O3· H2O): structure and vibrational spectrum, Demichelis, R.; Noel, Y.; Zicovich-Wilson, C. M.; Roetti, C.; Valenzano, L.; Dovesi, R., Journal of Physics: Conference Series, Volume 117, Issue 1, pp. 012013 (2008)., {{doi|10.1088/1742-6596/117/1/012013}}</ref>
