'''Philip Arthur Dominic Hollom''' (9 June 1912 – 20 June 2014) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[ornithologist]]. He was born in [[Bickley]], Kent, England,<ref name="BB:105;342-3">{{cite journal|last=Pitches|first=Adrian|date=June 2012|title=Phil Hollom at 100|journal=British Birds|volume=105|issue=6|pages=342–3|issn=0007-0335}}</ref><ref>''[[Contemporary Authors]].'' Volumes 15–16, [[Gale Research Company]], Detroit, Michigan 1966, page 214</ref> the second of five sons. His younger brother, Sir [[Jasper Hollom]], was [[Deputy Governor of the Bank of England]] from 1970 to 1980, having been [[Chief Cashier of the Bank of England]] from 1962 to 1966.<ref name="telegraph.co.uk">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/10946700/Phil-Hollom-obituary.html|title=Phil Hollom - obituary|website=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref>
In March 1951 he became a member of the editorial board of [[British Birds (magazine)|''British Birds'' magazine]]<ref name="BB:105;342-3" /> under the senior editorship of [[Max Nicholson]], whom he succeeded in 1960.<ref name="BB:105;342-3" /> Nicholson, who had remained on the editorial board, and Hollom stood down in 1972 and were replaced on the board by [[Ian Wallace (ornithologist)|Ian Wallace]] and [[Malcolm Ogilvie]].<ref name="BB:100,3-15">''A history of British Birds'', Malcolm Ogilvie, James Ferguson-Lees and Richard Chandler, [[British Birds (magazine)|''British Birds'']] 100 (2007) 3-15</ref>
Hollom was a Council member and Vice President of the [[Ornithological Society of the Middle East]].<ref name=OSME2004>{{cite web|url=http://www.osme.org/sand261/osmenews.html|title=OSME News, 2004|website=Osme.org|accessdate=1 August 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070325091035/http://www.osme.org/sand261/osmenews.html|archivedate=25 March 2007|df=}}</ref> He was the first chairman of the [[British Birds Rarities Committee]]<ref name="BB:105;342-3" /> and was awarded the [[British Trust for Ornithology]]'s Tucker Medal in 1954<ref name="BOU">{{cite web|url=http://www.bou.org.uk/about-the-bou/phil-hollom/ |title=Phil Hollom, 1912 - 2014 |publisher=British Ornithologists' Union |date=2014-06-23 |accessdate=2014-06-27}}</ref> and the [[British Ornithologists' Union]]'s Union Medal "for his outstanding contribution to the BOU and to ornithology" in 1984.<ref name="BOU" />
He lived in [[Hydestyle]], Surrey, from the mid-1980s until his death.<ref name="BB:105;342-3" /> He [[centenarian|turned 100]] in June 2012<ref name="Centenary">{{cite press release|title = Happy 100th birthday Phil Hollom!|publisher = [[British Trust for Ornithology]]|date = 2012-06-09|url = http://www.bto.org/news-events/news/happy-100th-birthday-phil-hollom|accessdate = 2012-07-18}}</ref> and died on 20 June 2014 at the age of 102.<ref name="BOU" /> He had been a member of the BOU for 81 years.<ref name="BOU" /> Hollom was survived by his daughter and two sons.<ref name="telegraph.co.uk"/>
